\title{Physics Problem: Wave Reflection and Transmission at a Boundary}
\author{}
\date{}
\maketitle

\section*{Problem Statement}

Two wires of different densities are joined as in Fig. 8.2. An incident wave 
\[
y_1 = A_1 \sin(\omega t - k_1 x)
\]
is travelling in the positive \(x\)-direction along the wire. At the boundary, this wave is partly transmitted. 

\begin{enumerate}
    \item[(a)] Find the reflected and transmitted amplitudes in terms of the incident amplitude.
    \item[(b)] Determine when the amplitude of the reflected wave will be negative.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{Solution}

\subsection*{(a) Reflected and Transmitted Amplitudes}

When a wave encounters a boundary between two media with different densities, part of the wave is reflected and part is transmitted. The incident wave is given by:
\[
y_1 = A_1 \sin(\omega t - k_1 x)
\]

The reflected wave can be expressed as:
\[
y_r = A_r \sin(\omega t + k_1 x)
\]

The transmitted wave can be expressed as:
\[
y_t = A_t \sin(\omega t - k_2 x)
\]

Using boundary conditions at the interface, we can relate the amplitudes:
\[
A_r = \frac{Z_2 - Z_1}{Z_2 + Z_1} A_1
\]
\[
A_t = \frac{2Z_2}{Z_2 + Z_1} A_1
\]

where \(Z_1\) and \(Z_2\) are the impedances of the two wires, given by \(Z = \rho v\), with \(\rho\) being the density and \(v\) the wave speed in the medium.

\subsection*{(b) Negative Amplitude of the Reflected Wave}

The amplitude of the reflected wave \(A_r\) will be negative when:
\[
Z_2 < Z_1
\]

This condition implies that the impedance of the second medium is less than that of the first medium, causing a phase inversion upon reflection.

