\end{equation}

Comparing with the expression for \( p(x, t) \), we see:

\begin{equation}
    \phi_p = \phi_s - \frac{\pi}{2}.
\end{equation}

This shows that the displacement is 90Â° out of phase with the pressure wave.

Finally, equating the amplitudes from the harmonic expressions, we have:

\begin{equation}
    p_0 = B s_0 k.
\end{equation}

Thus, the relationship between the pressure amplitude and the displacement amplitude is given by:

\begin{equation}
    s_0 = \frac{p_0}{B k}.
\end{equation}

